data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider blocked sync LINQ by default but let you opt back in with the `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Cosmos.SyncOverAsync` switch. **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed.** All synchronous LINQ operations (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`, etc.) against the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

## How to fix

Convert every synchronous call to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return `Task<T>` (or `Task` for void) and mark methods `async`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Rename methods with `Async` suffix by convention

The async methods come from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` namespace — make sure you have `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;`. Note that `async` will propagate up the call chain, so callers of these methods will also need updating.
